1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,595
Let's talk about cleaning health care dataset.

2
00:00:02,595 --> 00:00:04,860
In this demo, I'm going to walk through techniques for

3
00:00:04,860 --> 00:00:07,050
cleaning each major data quality issue,

4
00:00:07,050 --> 00:00:08,940
and cleaning a few tidiness issues.

5
00:00:08,940 --> 00:00:10,860
While we won't be able to cover how to clean

6
00:00:10,860 --> 00:00:14,115
every data quality issue within this dataset as there are a lot,

7
00:00:14,115 --> 00:00:15,270
you'll get an understanding of

8
00:00:15,270 --> 00:00:19,200
the problem-solving methodology that data wranglers use to approach cleaning data.

9
00:00:19,200 --> 00:00:23,715
For this demo, we're pulling our Phase II clinical trial dataset of the oral insulin.

10
00:00:23,715 --> 00:00:25,275
In almost all cases,

11
00:00:25,275 --> 00:00:29,295
it's strongly recommended to deal with missing data or completeness issues first,

12
00:00:29,295 --> 00:00:30,810
to get those out of the way.

13
00:00:30,810 --> 00:00:33,390
Then you can proceed to resolving messy data issues,

14
00:00:33,390 --> 00:00:37,650
and return back to resolving data quality issues. Let's get started.

15
00:00:37,650 --> 00:00:39,780
After importing our libraries,

16
00:00:39,780 --> 00:00:42,405
and reading in our data frames and tables,

17
00:00:42,405 --> 00:00:45,790
we're going to start with our completeness missing data issues first.

18
00:00:45,790 --> 00:00:48,205
During the assessment freeze for this dataset,

19
00:00:48,205 --> 00:00:50,450
we identify that there are missing records,

20
00:00:50,450 --> 00:00:54,470
280 instead of 350 records in the treatments data frame.

21
00:00:54,470 --> 00:00:56,420
This issue would trigger us to go back,

22
00:00:56,420 --> 00:00:58,130
and check if we gathered the data correctly,

23
00:00:58,130 --> 00:00:59,510
and retrieve the data again.

24
00:00:59,510 --> 00:01:03,095
In this case, we can gather more data to help address missing values.

25
00:01:03,095 --> 00:01:05,465
Let's say, we've now retrieved the missing data,

26
00:01:05,465 --> 00:01:09,250
which we've stored in a separate file called treatments_cut.csv.

27
00:01:09,250 --> 00:01:14,240
It contains 70 additional labels for all of the columns except hba1c_change,

28
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:15,670
which we'll return to later.

29
00:01:15,670 --> 00:01:19,880
Now we need to get these entries into our original treatments data frame.

30
00:01:19,880 --> 00:01:22,235
We can use the concat function for this,

31
00:01:22,235 --> 00:01:25,970
for which a default parameters will insert the columns from

32
00:01:25,970 --> 00:01:29,885
treatments cut.csv at the end of our original treatments data frame.

33
00:01:29,885 --> 00:01:32,750
Here we are inserting or concatenating treatments_clean,

34
00:01:32,750 --> 00:01:36,620
and treatments_cut, where treatments_clean is a copy of our treatments data frame.

35
00:01:36,620 --> 00:01:39,530
Now take a look at the outputs of the head,

36
00:01:39,530 --> 00:01:41,150
and the info function.

37
00:01:41,150 --> 00:01:44,105
Here we can clearly see that the values for every column,

38
00:01:44,105 --> 00:01:47,380
except this last one, are up to 350.

39
00:01:47,380 --> 00:01:53,480
Let's now actually address this missing values from our hemoglobin change entries.

40
00:01:53,480 --> 00:01:56,180
The hemoglobin level change is calculated, again,

41
00:01:56,180 --> 00:01:59,785
by subtracting the values from the start column and the end column.

42
00:01:59,785 --> 00:02:03,380
In this case, we don't actually have to impute the missing values,

43
00:02:03,380 --> 00:02:06,450
because we do have the original entries for the start and end values,

44
00:02:06,450 --> 00:02:10,105
so we can just calculate these accurately ourselves.

45
00:02:10,105 --> 00:02:14,390
Let's go ahead and create a new column by subtracting the values in

46
00:02:14,390 --> 00:02:20,165
the start column with the end column for our original hba1c_change column.

47
00:02:20,165 --> 00:02:25,870
Now we can see the missing data issue is fixed because our values are up to 350,

48
00:02:25,870 --> 00:02:30,290
and our data frame still looks intact when we're running a.sample method.

49
00:02:30,290 --> 00:02:33,180
Let's now go on to Step 2; tidiness.

50
00:02:33,180 --> 00:02:36,040
Now that we've dealt with the missing data first, in this section,

51
00:02:36,040 --> 00:02:39,490
we're going to deal with three tidiness issues that were identified on this dataset,

52
00:02:39,490 --> 00:02:42,145
plus one more we'll identify right on the spot.

53
00:02:42,145 --> 00:02:44,970
Our first issue that we're going to deal with is,

54
00:02:44,970 --> 00:02:47,145
contact column in the patient's table.

55
00:02:47,145 --> 00:02:52,465
As you can see, our contact column here is containing both the phone number and email.

56
00:02:52,465 --> 00:02:55,300
It should be split into two separate columns.

57
00:02:55,300 --> 00:02:57,310
We also see a potential problem.

58
00:02:57,310 --> 00:02:59,875
Sometimes phone numbers proceed email addresses,

59
00:02:59,875 --> 00:03:01,585
and sometimes vice versa.

60
00:03:01,585 --> 00:03:06,235
We have to be extremely careful with how we deal with this type of cases.

61
00:03:06,235 --> 00:03:08,680
We'll make a copy of the patient's data frame,

62
00:03:08,680 --> 00:03:11,590
and assign it to the patient's clean variable.

63
00:03:11,590 --> 00:03:12,790
Next, what we'll do is,

64
00:03:12,790 --> 00:03:15,550
use regex to extract the phone number and email

65
00:03:15,550 --> 00:03:18,775
variables from the contact column using regular expressions,

66
00:03:18,775 --> 00:03:21,570
and pandas str.extract method.

67
00:03:21,570 --> 00:03:26,475
We'll also want to drop the contact column when done. Let's get started.

68
00:03:26,475 --> 00:03:31,660
We're going to use the str.extract command to extract regex out of the contact column.

69
00:03:31,660 --> 00:03:34,885
We're going to set the expanded parameter to true,

70
00:03:34,885 --> 00:03:37,615
to expand this split strings into separate columns.

71
00:03:37,615 --> 00:03:41,695
Now you're probably wondering what this monstrous regex expression is.

72
00:03:41,695 --> 00:03:45,010
This regex was carefully crafted to detect phone numbers,

73
00:03:45,010 --> 00:03:49,505
no matter whether they're placed before or after the email addresses.

74
00:03:49,505 --> 00:03:52,825
Well, let's now try to detect the email addresses as well.

75
00:03:52,825 --> 00:03:55,810
We can use this particular block of regex to

76
00:03:55,810 --> 00:03:59,620
signify emails in the dataset all start and end with letters,

77
00:03:59,620 --> 00:04:02,240
and again use the expand=True command.

78
00:04:02,240 --> 00:04:06,160
This regex specifically is designed to catch email addresses,

79
00:04:06,160 --> 00:04:09,985
regardless of whether they're placed before or after the phone numbers.

80
00:04:09,985 --> 00:04:14,455
Using expand=True, we should have now created two columns,

81
00:04:14,455 --> 00:04:16,070
phone number and email.

82
00:04:16,070 --> 00:04:18,625
We want to also make sure that the contact column

83
00:04:18,625 --> 00:04:21,220
is dropped after creating these two separate columns,

84
00:04:21,220 --> 00:04:24,850
which we do here with.drop, and setting axis=1.

85
00:04:24,850 --> 00:04:28,565
Let's look at the first few rows of this cleaned data frame.

86
00:04:28,565 --> 00:04:31,770
Visually, we can already see the context column has gone.

87
00:04:31,770 --> 00:04:34,850
We can pull up a quick sample using.sample,

88
00:04:34,850 --> 00:04:36,830
and see in the phone number column that,

89
00:04:36,830 --> 00:04:38,840
there aren't any email addresses.

90
00:04:38,840 --> 00:04:42,710
Now we see clear separation between phone numbers and email addresses.

91
00:04:42,710 --> 00:04:47,570
You can also use.sort_values to confirm that no emails are starting with an integer,

92
00:04:47,570 --> 00:04:51,595
as that regex expression that we used didn't match for this.

93
00:04:51,595 --> 00:04:54,170
Let's move on to tighten this issue number 2.

94
00:04:54,170 --> 00:04:57,860
We have three variables in the auralin and novodra columns in the treatments table;

95
00:04:57,860 --> 00:05:00,770
treatment, start_dose, and end_dose.

96
00:05:00,770 --> 00:05:02,155
We're going to use on pivoting,

97
00:05:02,155 --> 00:05:03,840
and other operations to help us.

98
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:06,680
Let's go ahead and get started with the on pivoting using melting.

99
00:05:06,680 --> 00:05:10,825
Here, I define id_vars as the given_name, surnames, start, end,

100
00:05:10,825 --> 00:05:15,110
and change columns, which are all columns we want to keep intact.

101
00:05:15,110 --> 00:05:17,915
Then we define our variable name as treatment,

102
00:05:17,915 --> 00:05:19,685
and our value name is dose.

103
00:05:19,685 --> 00:05:22,520
Now our auralin and novodra column headers have been

104
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:26,450
transformed into the treatment column as you can see here,

105
00:05:26,450 --> 00:05:29,705
indicating the type of the drug that a person took as values.

106
00:05:29,705 --> 00:05:31,850
We also see our dose is a separate column,

107
00:05:31,850 --> 00:05:33,895
and the rest of the columns are intact.

108
00:05:33,895 --> 00:05:35,985
There is still work to do here though.

109
00:05:35,985 --> 00:05:37,260
We don't need these hyphens,

110
00:05:37,260 --> 00:05:42,335
and we need to split the dose into start and end doses and integers. Let's do this.

111
00:05:42,335 --> 00:05:46,130
We first select the dose column from the treatments_clean data frame,

112
00:05:46,130 --> 00:05:51,960
then we use.str.split to split the start and end doses.

113
00:05:51,960 --> 00:05:54,585
We're going to go ahead and split it on the hyphen.

114
00:05:54,585 --> 00:05:57,260
Here we're seeing that, that is the delimiter that's been provided

115
00:05:57,260 --> 00:05:59,900
as the first argument that's going to be used to separate the values.

116
00:05:59,900 --> 00:06:02,375
N=1 is indicating that,

117
00:06:02,375 --> 00:06:06,265
only the first occurrence of the delimiter should be used for the split.

118
00:06:06,265 --> 00:06:09,095
expand=True, again, is allowing us to

119
00:06:09,095 --> 00:06:12,260
return a data frame with separate and values in different columns.

120
00:06:12,260 --> 00:06:15,155
We want to have a data frame in the end with two columns.

121
00:06:15,155 --> 00:06:18,685
We'll call the first column dose_start and the second one dose_end.

122
00:06:18,685 --> 00:06:20,810
Now that it's split into two columns, again,

123
00:06:20,810 --> 00:06:25,480
we want to drop the original dose column using the drop method using axis=1,

124
00:06:25,480 --> 00:06:27,050
to indicate it's a column.

125
00:06:27,050 --> 00:06:29,900
Looking at the data frame after these operations,

126
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:32,810
we have a treatment column that is neat,

127
00:06:32,810 --> 00:06:35,180
that is showing us which drug the patient took,

128
00:06:35,180 --> 00:06:37,250
and the start, and the end dose.

129
00:06:37,250 --> 00:06:39,595
This is a much better data structure.

130
00:06:39,595 --> 00:06:42,160
Now let's take a look at another issue.

131
00:06:42,160 --> 00:06:45,290
The adverse reaction tables should be part of the treatments table,

132
00:06:45,290 --> 00:06:48,485
because they have the same observational unit in individual treatment.

133
00:06:48,485 --> 00:06:51,995
Let's merge the adverse reaction column to the treatment table,

134
00:06:51,995 --> 00:06:54,535
joining on given name and surname.

135
00:06:54,535 --> 00:06:58,100
In this case, the how parameter is set to left,

136
00:06:58,100 --> 00:06:59,660
which means that all rows from

137
00:06:59,660 --> 00:07:03,080
the left data frame treatments_clean are included in the resulting data frame,

138
00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:05,240
and only the matching rows from the right data frame,

139
00:07:05,240 --> 00:07:07,315
adverse_reactions_clean, are included.

140
00:07:07,315 --> 00:07:08,760
Printing this data frame,

141
00:07:08,760 --> 00:07:10,270
we now see the tables are merged,

142
00:07:10,270 --> 00:07:13,925
with a new adverse reaction column appearing in the treatments clean table.

143
00:07:13,925 --> 00:07:16,260
Let's put aside these two tables,

144
00:07:16,260 --> 00:07:19,690
and focus primarily on the treatments clean and patients clean table,

145
00:07:19,690 --> 00:07:21,805
as part of a final tidiness issue.

146
00:07:21,805 --> 00:07:24,100
The given name and surname columns in

147
00:07:24,100 --> 00:07:27,100
the patient's table is duplicated in the treatments table.

148
00:07:27,100 --> 00:07:28,570
You can see that here, given name,

149
00:07:28,570 --> 00:07:29,590
surname and patients,

150
00:07:29,590 --> 00:07:31,495
and given name, surname and treatments.

151
00:07:31,495 --> 00:07:33,400
But in the treatments_clean data frame,

152
00:07:33,400 --> 00:07:37,915
these names are in lowercase as opposed to the patients_clean data frame.

153
00:07:37,915 --> 00:07:40,630
Our objective is to get the name columns removed and treatments,

154
00:07:40,630 --> 00:07:43,150
and replace them with a single patient ID column,

155
00:07:43,150 --> 00:07:45,430
keeping the patient's name as part of the patient's table,

156
00:07:45,430 --> 00:07:48,115
so the observational units are neatly set.

157
00:07:48,115 --> 00:07:52,870
Note that right now the treatments table does not have a patient ID column.

158
00:07:52,870 --> 00:07:56,815
First, let's get the patients_clean columns here,

159
00:07:56,815 --> 00:07:59,120
from the patients_clean data frame including the ID,

160
00:07:59,120 --> 00:08:00,940
the given name, and the surname.

161
00:08:00,940 --> 00:08:04,070
We're going to assign this to a variable called id_names,

162
00:08:04,070 --> 00:08:09,155
and then use str.lower to convert these to lowercase for the given name and the surname.

163
00:08:09,155 --> 00:08:12,595
Next we're going to use pandas merge function,

164
00:08:12,595 --> 00:08:16,490
and merge the treatments_clean data frame and the id_names variable

165
00:08:16,490 --> 00:08:20,315
that we recently created on our given name and surname columns.

166
00:08:20,315 --> 00:08:22,190
Next, we finally want to drop

167
00:08:22,190 --> 00:08:24,620
the given name and surname columns from the treatments data frame,

168
00:08:24,620 --> 00:08:27,365
because we, again, only want them in the patient's data frame.

169
00:08:27,365 --> 00:08:31,040
Let's now confirm that the treatments table only has the patient ID,

170
00:08:31,040 --> 00:08:32,345
and not the given name and surname,

171
00:08:32,345 --> 00:08:33,980
which we can immediately see here.

172
00:08:33,980 --> 00:08:35,270
With our patient's table,

173
00:08:35,270 --> 00:08:38,295
we have both the patient ID and the given name and surname.

174
00:08:38,295 --> 00:08:42,065
Now we have all our information about patients in one table, the patient's table,

175
00:08:42,065 --> 00:08:45,085
and all the information about treatments in our treatments table,

176
00:08:45,085 --> 00:08:48,440
with the patient ID helping us link between the two.

